{
  "text": "Mucosal perforation is a rare intraoperative complication of Ramstedt's pyloromyotomy and usually results from extending the myotomy beyond the pyloric-duodenal junction and is indicated by the appearance of bilious fluid. When this occurs, repair is done by using interrupted fine monofilament long-term absorbable sutures placed transversely and covered with omentum [CITATION_1] . In our series, intraoperative mucosal perforations were reported in 5.9 % of cases, a figure which is higher than that reported in literature [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . A high figure of 10.9 % was reported by Tadesse and Gadisa [CITATION_5] in Ethiopia. This observation calls for meticulous care to be taken when performing Ramstedt's pyloromyotomy to prevent mucosal perforation, especially at the lower end of the incision (pyloric-duodenal junction).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "879752",
    "[CITATION_2]": "43171994",
    "[CITATION_3]": "879752",
